## 🔢 SHA-256 Explained Step by Step

SHA-256 processes your document in 512-bit chunks through 64 rounds of mathematical transformations:

```
Your document (any size)
        │
        ▼
[PADDING] — Add bits to make length ≡ 448 (mod 512)
        │
        ▼
[512-bit BLOCKS] — Split into chunks
        │
        ▼
[INITIAL HASH VALUES] — 8 constants derived from prime numbers
h0 = 6a09e667, h1 = bb67ae85, h2 = 3c6ef372, h3 = a54ff53a
h4 = 510e527f, h5 = 9b05688c, h6 = 1f83d9ab, h7 = 5be0cd19
        │
        ▼
[64 ROUNDS] — Per block, using 64 round constants (k[0..63])
Each round: σ₀, σ₁, Σ₀, Σ₁, Ch, Maj operations (bitwise)
        │
        ▼
[COMPRESS] — Add round output to running hash values
        │
        ▼
[FINAL] — Concatenate h0-h7 → 256 bits = 64 hex chars
```

**Result:** `a591a6d40bf420404a011733cfb7b190d62c65bf0bcda32b57b277d9ad9f146e`

